{"award_age":61.0,"bio_image":"full\/1ca55b97ed7ced39d34b94b19653f40209ac021a.jpg","category":"Chemistry","country":"Canada","date_of_birth":"1932-04-26T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2000-10-04T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/d\/d6\/Michaelsmith.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Michael_Smith_(chemist)","mini_bio":"<p><b>Michael Smith<\/b> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_Canada\" title=\"Order of Canada\">CC<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_British_Columbia\" title=\"Order of British Columbia\">OBC<\/a>, FRS (April 26, 1932 \u2013 October 4, 2000) was a British-born Canadian biochemist and businessman. He was the winner of the 1993 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> (shared with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kary_Mullis\" title=\"Kary Mullis\">Kary Mullis<\/a>) for his work in developing <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Site-directed_mutagenesis\" title=\"Site-directed mutagenesis\">site-directed mutagenesis<\/a>. Following graduation with a PhD in 1956 from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Manchester\" title=\"University of Manchester\">University of Manchester<\/a>, he undertook post-doctoral studies with Dr. <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Har_Gobind_Khorana\" title=\"Har Gobind Khorana\">Har Gobind Khorana<\/a> (himself a Nobel Prize winner) at the British Columbia Research Council in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vancouver\" title=\"Vancouver\">Vancouver<\/a>, Canada. Subsequently, Smith worked at the Fisheries Research Board of Canada Laboratory in Vancouver before being appointed a professor of biochemistry in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/UBC_Faculty_of_Medicine\" title=\"UBC Faculty of Medicine\">UBC Faculty of Medicine<\/a> in 1966.<\/p><p>Smith's career included roles as the founding director of the UBC Biotechnology Laboratory (1987 to 1995) and the founding scientific leader of the Protein Engineering Network of Centres of Excellence (PENCE). In 1996 he was named <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Peter_Wall_(property_developer)\" title=\"Peter Wall (property developer)\">Peter Wall<\/a> Distinguished Professor of Biotechnology. Subsequently he became the founding director of the Genome Sequencing Centre (now called the Genome Sciences Centre) at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/BC_Cancer_Research_Centre\" title=\"BC Cancer Research Centre\">BC Cancer Research Centre<\/a>.<\/p><p>Smith received many awards in addition to the Nobel Prize, and was known for his generosity. He donated half of the Nobel Prize money to researchers working on the genetics of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Schizophrenia\" title=\"Schizophrenia\">schizophrenia<\/a>. The other half he gave to BC <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Science_World_(Vancouver)\" title=\"Science World (Vancouver)\">Science World<\/a> and to the Society for Canadian Women in Science and Technology. He received the Royal Bank Award in 1999, and donated the companion grant to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/BC_Cancer_Foundation\" title=\"BC Cancer Foundation\" class=\"mw-redirect\">BC Cancer Foundation<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Michael_Smith_(chemist)#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Michael_Smith_(chemist)#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Michael Smith","place_of_birth":"Blackpool ,  England","place_of_death":"Vancouver ,  British Columbia ,  Canada","text":"Michael Smith ,  born in the United Kingdom , Chemistry, 1993","year":1993.0}